### useMemo

`useMemo` memoizes the result of an expensive computation, recalculating only when dependencies change. It optimizes performance by avoiding unnecessary calculations.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useMemo } from 'react';

const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => {
  return expensiveComputation(a, b);
}, [a, b]);
```

### Example

```jsx
function Dashboard({ transactions }) {
  const total = useMemo(() => {
    return transactions.reduce((sum, t) => sum + t.amount, 0);
  }, [transactions]);

  const average = useMemo(() => {
    return transactions.length > 0 ? total / transactions.length : 0;
  }, [total, transactions.length]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Total: ${total}</p>
      <p>Average: ${average.toFixed(2)}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### When to Use

| Use Case | Example |
|----------|---------|
| Expensive calculations | Filtering, sorting large arrays |
| Creating objects/arrays for child props | Memoize reference to prevent child re-render |
| Derived state | Computing values from complex state |

### When NOT to Use

- Simple calculations (addition, string concat)
- Primitive values that rarely change
- Without profiling evidence of a bottleneck

> **Key Point:** useMemo is a performance optimization, not a guarantee. React may recalculate values if memory is needed. Do not rely on useMemo for correctness; use it to avoid expensive calculations.

